<styl>by <m2>By <m0>TERRY LAWSON<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Knight-Ridder News Service<ep>
   <m0>G<m2><ql>
<m0>ive Sharon Stone this: She knows who she is.<ep>
   ``I just don't figure that my role here is to make things easy for anyone,'' Stone says flatly. ``If you can't handle that, then you can't handle me. But if you can, we can usually make something happen.''<ep>
   It is, after all, Sharon Stone, who maybe lost the Academy Award to Susan Sarandon, who maybe makes a half-million dollars less per picture than Demi Moore, but who still is the biggest female movie star in the United States and perhaps the only one who might be able to open a film like <m0>Last Dance<m0>. If <m0>Casino<m0> was Stone's opportunity to show the world she is something more than a celluloid aphrodisiac, <m0>Last Dance<m0> is her shot at showing she can do it without the sex.<ep>
   ``Hey, I'm not stupid,'' says Stone, letting you know she knows you know she isn't. ``This is not the kind of role that someone reads and says `I know, let's go out and get Sharon Stone!' ''<ep>
   Which is why Stone wanted to play Cindy Liggett, a convicted killer awaiting execution in some unnamed Southern state with a governor who has never granted clemency. Therefore, when a naive state lawyer, played by Rob Morrow, shows up offering hope of clemency or a stay, Cindy thinks him a fool. But he persists, and eventually the two form a relationship that changes both their lives in unexpected ways.<ep>
   Or not so unexpected, in the wake of the acclaimed <m0>Dead Man Walking<m0>, for which Sarandon won the Academy Award that could have gone to Stone. In <m0>Last Dance<m0>, the sex of the convict and the convict's champion have been reversed, but the tale itself is strikingly similar. Stone says she was unaware of the other project when she took the role, but would have taken the part anyway.<ep>
   ``Bruce [director Bruce Beresford] came to see me in Las Vegas when I was shooting <m0>Casino<m0>, which was the most demanding, exhaustive work I had ever done,'' says Stone. ``And reading the script, I had no doubt that playing a character like Cindy Liggett was going to be every bit as difficult. So I was naturally wary, and just as amazed as anyone else would be that he would think of me for the part. The obvious question was, `Why me?' Bruce said, `Because I want to make my job as easy as possible.'<ep>
   ``He believed in me so much more than I do, and when you have that kind of trust from someone, you can do the work of which you are capable. Sounds so simple, doesn't <m2><ql>
