<m0>it? You'd think more directors would try it.''<ep>
   ``Sure, I know that on occasions people have been intimidated by the force of my personality, or what they believe about me, but my job is not to make them feel safe and secure. My job is to do the best work I can, no matter what it takes to get there. The best directors I have worked with, Marty [Martin Scorsese], Bruce and Mark Rydell, are all people who are confident enough with themselves and their vision to use simple honesty. These are people who will let you follow your instincts, try what you think is right, and then say `Honey, that's not the way to go. Now try this, and you might get there.'<ep>
   ``It's my experience that you really can't lose when you try the truth. There's a shocking revelation: When in doubt, go for the truth.''<ep>
<m1>Death row research<ep>
<m0>   Stone said that was her beacon when searching for the soul of Liggett, who she says was a composite of ``three or four actual cases, and some of the people I saw and met.'' Her research included watching a documentary on female death row inmates, and then talking to some convicted killers. At Tennessee State Prison, where some of the scenes were filmed, Stone was locked down in maximum security, an experience she calls, with some intended irony, ``enlightening.''<ep>
   ``I went into the film with ambiguity, feeling unclear as to what was appropriate,'' Stone says, regarding her personal views on capital punishment. ``I didn't come out that way. It wasn't just playing the part of a character who was going to be executed, either, it was coming to terms with a system that sanctions killing those who have crossed that line to kill someone else. In the case of Cindy, she was not the same person who has committed those terrible crimes. Prison was the first safe and consistent place she had ever been in her life, and in that environment, she was able to see who she was and what she was capable of. Then they want to kill her.''<ep>
   Stone says she surprised Beresford and the crew when she showed up on the set ready to work: She had already mastered a Tennessee accent. She also had gone to her Madison Avenue hair stylist and ordered her to cut her hair ``really badly.''<ep>
   ``The first time, she couldn't bear to completely do it,'' Stone recalls, laughing. ``She got about two-thirds of the way there, so I made her do it again.'' Stone also had dyed her hair a shade she refers to as Ozark brown.<ep>
<m1>`Diabolique' tensions<ep>
<m0>   After <m0>Last Dance<m0>, Stone returned to Pennsylvania, where she was born in 1958, to make <m0>Diabolique<m0>, an experience that turned out to be less than satisfying. After she balked at doing a nude scene the producer said was contractually required, tensions ran high on the set.<ep>
   When the film was released last month, Stone declined to publicize it. Indeed, the only time during this interview Stone shows any of that famous bristle is when the word ``contract'' comes up: ``I'm not going there,'' she says. ``This is supposed to be about <m0>Last Dance<m0>.''<ep>
      But she also knows that any Stone interview is about Stone, and is aware of her ability to polarize the public.<ep>
   ``Actually, I think it's that level of fame that polarizes people,'' says Stone. ``The perception at that level tends to be larger than life, so everything you do is exaggerated. But I'm telling you, whether it's you or me or Bob Smith, if you're one of those people who fills a room when you enter it, it means other people get pushed aside and have less of that room, and a lot of people feel smaller when that happens.<ep>
   ``So, if you're a room filler, are you supposed to feel guilty, or try to slink to the corner? No, you want to be what you can be. Do I know that I bug the living s--- out of some people? Sure, I know that. But I also know that my job isn't necessarily to make people feel good about me, or about themselves. It's just to make them feel.''<ep>
